Having Caesar before his eyes, he could not but look upon Pompey as the pillar of the republic and the old aristocracy Í¾ but whether he was right in so doing, is a question which, considering the historical facts of the case, it is difficult to decide. Pompey was no less ambitious and anxious to obtain power than his great opponent, and his defeat could raise him only in the eyes of one who was an enthusiastic admirer of the ancient forms of the republic.
